[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] In mechatronics engineering, the **Denavit–Hartenberg parameters** (also called **DH parameters**) are the four parameters associated with the DH convention for attaching reference frames to the links of a spatial kinematic chain, or robot manipulator.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Jacques Denavit and Richard Hartenberg introduced this convention in 1955 in order to standardize the coordinate frames for spatial linkages.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Richard Paul demonstrated its value for the kinematic analysis of robotic systems in 1981.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] While many conventions for attaching reference frames have been developed, the Denavit–Hartenberg convention remains a popular approach.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] A commonly used convention for selecting frames of reference in robotics applications is the **Denavit and Hartenberg (D–H) convention** which was introduced by Jacques Denavit and Richard S.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] In this convention, coordinate frames are attached to the joints between two links such that one transformation is associated with the joint [*Z* ], and the second is associated with the link [*X* ].
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where [*T* ] is the transformation that characterizes the location and orientation of the end-link.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] To determine the coordinate transformations [*Z* ] and [*X* ], the joints connecting the links are modeled as either hinged or sliding joints, each of which has a unique line S in space that forms the joint axis and define the relative movement of the two links.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] A typical serial robot is characterized by a sequence of six lines *Si* (*i* = 1, 2, ..., 6), one for each joint in the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] For each sequence of lines Si and *S**i*+1, there is a common normal line *A**i*,*i*+1.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The system of six joint axes Si and five common normal lines *A**i*,*i*+1 form the kinematic skeleton of the typical six degree-of-freedom serial robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Denavit and Hartenberg introduced the convention that z-coordinate axes are assigned to the joint axes Si and x-coordinate axes are assigned to the common normals *A**i*,*i*+1.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where θi is the rotation around and di is the sliding motion along the z-axis.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Each of these parameters could be a constant depending on the structure of the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where *α**i*,*i*+1 and *r**i*,*i*+1 define the physical dimensions of the link in terms of the angle measured around and distance measured along the X axis.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The x-axis is parallel to the common normal: $x_{n}=z_{n}\times z_{n-1}$ (or away from *z**n*–1) If there is no unique common normal (parallel z axes), then d (below) is a free parameter.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The direction of xn is from *z**n*–1 to zn, as shown in the video below.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] 3. the y-axis follows from the x- and z-axes by choosing it to be a right-handed coordinate system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] There is some choice in frame layout as to whether the previous x axis or the next x points along the common normal.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The latter system allows branching chains more efficiently, as multiple frames can all point away from their common ancestor, but in the alternative layout the ancestor can only point toward one successor.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Thus the commonly used notation places each down-chain x axis collinear with the common normal, yielding the transformation calculations shown below.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Using this notation, each link can be described by a coordinate transformation from the concurrent coordinate system to the previous coordinate system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Note that this is the product of two screw displacements.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where *R* is the 3×3 submatrix describing rotation and *T* is the 3×1 submatrix describing translation.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] In some books, the order of transformation for a pair of consecutive rotation and translation (such as $d_{n}$ and $\theta _{n}$ ) is reversed.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] This is possible (despite the fact that in general, matrix multiplication is not commutative) since translations and rotations are concerned with the same axes $z_{n-1}$ and $x_{n}$ , respectively.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] As matrix multiplication order for these pairs does not matter, the result is the same.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The Denavit and Hartenberg notation gives a standard (distal) methodology to write the kinematic equations of a manipulator.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] This is especially useful for serial manipulators where a matrix is used to represent the pose (position and orientation) of one body with respect to another.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Where the upper left $3\times 3$ submatrix of M represents the relative orientation of the two bodies, and the upper right $3\times 1$ represents their relative position or more specifically the body position in frame *n* − 1 represented with element of frame *n*.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where $R^{T}$ is both the transpose and the inverse of the orthogonal matrix R , i.e. $R_{ij}^{-1}=R_{ij}^{T}=R_{ji}$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Further matrices can be defined to represent velocity and acceleration of bodies.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] where $\omega$ is the angular velocity of body j with respect to body i and all the components are expressed in frame k ; v is the velocity of one point of body j with respect to body i (the pole).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The pole is the point of j passing through the origin of frame i .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] in other words the absolute velocity is the sum of the parent velocity plus the relative velocity; for the acceleration the Coriolis' term is also present.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] For the dynamics, three further matrices are necessary to describe the inertia J , the linear and angular momentum $\Gamma$ , and the forces and torques $\Phi$ applied to a body.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] All the matrices are represented with the vector components in a certain frame k .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The matrices described allow the writing of the dynamic equations in a concise way.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Some books such as *Introduction to Robotics: Mechanics and Control (3rd Edition)* use modified (proximal) DH parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The difference between the classic (distal) DH parameters and the modified DH parameters are the locations of the coordinates system attachment to the links and the order of the performed transformations.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Compared with the classic DH parameters, the coordinates of frame $O_{i-1}$ is put on axis *i* − 1, not the axis *i* in classic DH convention.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] The coordinates of $O_{i}$ is put on the axis *i*, not the axis *i* + 1 in classic DH convention.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Note that some books (e.g.:) use $a_{n}$ and $\alpha _{n}$ to indicate the length and twist of link *n* − 1 rather than link *n*.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] As a consequence, ${}^{n-1}T_{n}$ is formed only with parameters using the same subscript.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/denavit-hartenberg-parameters] Surveys of DH conventions and its differences have been published.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] In robot kinematics, **forward kinematics** refers to the use of the kinematic equations of a robot to compute the position of the end-effector from specified values for the joint parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] The kinematics equations of the robot are used in robotics, computer games, and animation.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] The reverse process, that computes the joint parameters that achieve a specified position of the end-effector, is known as inverse kinematics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] The kinematics equations for the series chain of a robot are obtained using a rigid transformation [Z] to characterize the relative movement allowed at each joint and separate rigid transformation [X] to define the dimensions of each link.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] where [T] is the transformation locating the end-link.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] These equations are called the kinematics equations of the serial chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] In 1955, Jacques Denavit and Richard Hartenberg introduced a convention for the definition of the joint matrices [Z] and link matrices [X] to standardize the coordinate frame for spatial linkages.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] where *θi*, *di*, *αi,i+1* and *ai,i+1* are known as the Denavit-Hartenberg parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] where ${}^{i-1}T_{i}(\theta _{i})$ is the transformation matrix from the frame of link i to link $i-1$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] In robotics, these are conventionally described by Denavit–Hartenberg parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] The forward kinematic equations can be used as a method in 3D computer graphics for animating models.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] The essential concept of forward kinematic animation is that the positions of particular parts of the model at a specified time are calculated from the position and orientation of the object, together with any information on the joints of an articulated model.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] So for example if the object to be animated is an arm with the shoulder remaining at a fixed location, the location of the tip of the thumb would be calculated from the angles of the shoulder, elbow, wrist, thumb and knuckle joints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] Three of these joints (the shoulder, wrist and the base of the thumb) have more than one degree of freedom, all of which must be taken into account.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] If the model were an entire human figure, then the location of the shoulder would also have to be calculated from other properties of the model.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] Forward kinematic animation can be distinguished from inverse kinematic animation by this means of calculation - in inverse kinematics the orientation of articulated parts is calculated from the desired position of certain points on the model.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/forward-kinematics] It is also distinguished from other animation systems by the fact that the motion of the model is defined directly by the animator - no account is taken of any physical laws that might be in effect on the model, such as gravity or collision with other models.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] IK operations are computationally much more complex than forward kinematics, in which joint parameters are trigonometrically calculated to achieve the position and orientation of the chain's end.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] In robotics, inverse kinematics makes use of the kinematics equations to determine the joint parameters that provide a desired configuration (position and rotation) for each of the robot's end effectors.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] This is important because robot tasks are performed with the end effectors, while control effort applies to the joints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Determining the movement of a robot so that its end effectors move from an initial configuration to a desired configuration is known as motion planning.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics transforms the motion plan into joint actuator trajectories for the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Similar formulas determine the positions of the skeleton of an animated character that is to move in a particular way in a film, or of a vehicle such as a car or boat containing the camera which is shooting a scene of a film.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The movement of a kinematic chain, whether it is a robot or an animated character, is modeled by the kinematics equations of the chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These equations define the configuration of the chain in terms of its joint parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Forward kinematics uses the joint parameters to compute the configuration of the chain, and inverse kinematics reverses this calculation to determine the joint parameters that achieve a desired configuration.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis is one of the first steps in the design of most industrial robots.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis allows the designer to obtain information on the position of each component within the mechanical system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] This information is necessary for subsequent dynamic analysis along with control paths.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is an example of the kinematic analysis of a constrained system of rigid bodies, or kinematic chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The kinematic equations of a robot can be used to define the loop equations of a complex articulated system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These loop equations are nonlinear constraints on the configuration parameters of the system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The independent parameters in these equations are known as the degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] While analytical solutions to the inverse kinematics problem exist for a wide range of kinematic chains, computer modeling and animation tools often use Newton's method to solve the nonlinear kinematics equations.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] When trying to find an analytical solution it is often convenient to exploit the geometry of the system and decompose it using subproblems with known solutions.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Other applications of inverse kinematic algorithms include interactive manipulation, animation control and collision avoidance.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is important to game programming and 3D animation, where it is used to connect game characters physically to the world, such as feet landing firmly on top of terrain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] An animated figure is modeled with a skeleton of rigid segments connected with joints, called a kinematic chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The kinematics equations of the figure define the relationship between the joint angles of the figure and its pose or configuration.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The forward kinematic animation problem uses the kinematics equations to determine the pose given the joint angles.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The *inverse kinematics problem* computes the joint angles for a desired pose of the figure.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] It is often easier for computer-based designers, artists, and animators to define the spatial configuration of an assembly or figure by moving parts, or arms and legs, rather than directly manipulating joint angles.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Therefore, inverse kinematics is used in computer-aided design systems to animate assemblies and by computer-based artists and animators to position figures and characters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The assembly is modeled as rigid links connected by joints that are defined as mates, or geometric constraints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Movement of one element requires the computation of the joint angles for the other elements to maintain the joint constraints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] For example, inverse kinematics allows an artist to move the hand of a 3D human model to a desired position and orientation and have an algorithm select the proper angles of the wrist, elbow, and shoulder joints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Successful implementation of computer animation usually also requires that the figure move within reasonable anthropomorphic limits.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] A method of comparing both forward and inverse kinematics for the animation of a character can be defined by the advantages inherent to each.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] For instance, blocking animation where large motion arcs are used is often more advantageous in forward kinematics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] However, more delicate animation and positioning of the target end effector in relation to other models might be easier using inverted kinematics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Modern digital creation packages (DCC) offer methods to apply both forward and inverse kinematics to models.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] In some, but not all cases, there exist analytical solutions to inverse kinematic problems.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] One such example is for a robot with 6 degrees of freedom (DOF) (for example, 6 revolute joints) moving in 3D space (with 3-position DOF, and 3 rotational DOF).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] If the DOF of the robot equals or exceeds that of the end effector, for example with a 7-DoF robot with 7 revolute joints, then there exist infinitely many solutions to the IK problem and an analytical solution does not exist.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Further extending this example, it is possible to fix one joint and analytically solve for the other joints, but a better solution is perhaps offered by numerical methods, which can instead optimize a solution given additional preferences (costs in an optimization problem).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] An analytic solution to an inverse kinematics problem is a closed-form expression that takes the end-effector pose as input and gives joint positions as output, $q=f(x)$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Analytical inverse kinematics solvers can be significantly faster than numerical solvers and provide more than one solution, but only a finite number of solutions, for a given end-effector pose.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Many different programs (Such as FOSS programs IKFast and Inverse Kinematics Library) are able to solve these problems quickly and efficiently using different algorithms such as the FABRIK solver.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] One issue with these solvers, is that they are known to not necessarily give locally smooth solutions between two adjacent configurations, which can cause instability if iterative solutions to inverse kinematics are required, such as if the IK is solved inside a high-rate control loop.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Many industrial 6DOF robots feature three rotational joints with intersecting axes ("spherical wrist").
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These robots, known as robots with an "Ortho-parallel Basis and a Spherical Wrist," can be defined by 7 kinematic parameters that are distances in their assumed standard geometry.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These robots may have up to 8 independent solutions for any given position and rotation of the robot tool head.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Open-source solutions for C++ and Rust exist.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] OPW has also been integrated into ROS framework.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] There are many methods of modelling and solving inverse kinematics problems.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The most flexible of these methods typically rely on iterative optimization to seek out an approximate solution, due to the difficulty of inverting the forward kinematics equation and the possibility of an empty solution space.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The core idea behind several of these methods is to model the forward kinematics equation using a Taylor series expansion, which can be simpler to invert and solve than the original system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique is a simple yet effective way of implementing inverse kinematics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Let there be m variables that govern the forward-kinematics equation, i.e. the position function.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These variables may be joint angles, lengths, or other arbitrary real values.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] If, for example, the IK system lives in a 3-dimensional space, the position function can be viewed as a mapping $p(x):\mathbb {R} ^{m}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique iteratively computes an estimate of $\Delta x$ that minimizes the error given by $||p(x_{0}+\Delta x_{\text{estimate}})-p_{1}||$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] where $J_{p}(x_{0})$ is the (3 × m) Jacobian matrix of the position function at $x_{0}$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] where $p_{i}(x)$ gives the i-th component of the position function, $x_{0,k}+h$ is simply $x_{0}$ with a small delta added to its k-th component, and h is a reasonably small positive value.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Applying the inverse Jacobian method once will result in a very rough estimate of the desired $\Delta x$ -vector.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] A line search should be used to scale this $\Delta x$ to an acceptable value.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Once some $\Delta x$ -vector has caused the error to drop close to zero, the algorithm should terminate.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] Existing methods based on the Hessian matrix of the system have been reported to converge to desired $\Delta x$ values using fewer iterations, though, in some cases more computational resources.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The inverse kinematics problem can also be approximated using heuristic methods.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] These methods perform simple, iterative operations to gradually lead to an approximation of the solution.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The heuristic algorithms have low computational cost (return the final pose very quickly), and usually support joint constraints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/inverse-kinematics] The most popular heuristic algorithms are cyclic coordinate descent (CCD) and forward and backward reaching inverse kinematics (FABRIK).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In vector calculus, the **Jacobian matrix** (/dʒəˈkoʊbiən/, /dʒɪ-, jɪ-/) of a vector-valued function of several variables is the matrix of all its first-order partial derivatives.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If this matrix is square, that is, if the number of variables equals the number of components of function values, then its determinant is called the **Jacobian determinant**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Both the matrix and (if applicable) the determinant are often referred to simply as the **Jacobian**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] They are named after Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi (1804-1851).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian matrix is the natural generalization of the derivative and the differential of a usual function to vector valued functions of several variables.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant is fundamentally used for changes of variables in multiple integrals.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Let ${\textstyle \mathbf {f}$ be a function such that each of its first-order partial derivatives exists on ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{n}}$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian matrix, whose entries are functions of **x**, is denoted in various ways; other common notations include *D***f**, $\nabla \mathbf {f}$ , and ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial (f_{1},\ldots ,f_{m})}{\partial (x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})}}}$ .
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Some authors define the Jacobian as the transpose of the form given above.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian matrix represents the total derivative of **f** at every point where **f** is differentiable.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In detail, if **h** is a displacement vector represented by a column matrix, the matrix product **Jf**(**x**) ⋅ **h** is another displacement vector, that is the best linear approximation of the change of **f** along **h** in a neighborhood of **x**, if **f**(**x**) is differentiable at **x**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] When ${\textstyle m=n}$ , the Jacobian matrix is square, so its determinant is a well-defined function of **x**, known as the **Jacobian determinant** of **f**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] It carries important information about the local behavior of **f**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In particular, the function **f** has a differentiable inverse function in a neighborhood of a point **x** if and only if the Jacobian determinant is nonzero at **x** (see inverse function theorem for an explanation of this and Jacobian conjecture for a related problem of *global* invertibility).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant also appears when changing the variables in multiple integrals (see substitution rule for multiple variables).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Specializing further, when ${\textstyle m=n=1}$ , that is when ${\textstyle f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} }$ is a scalar-valued function of a single variable, the Jacobian matrix has a single entry; this entry is the derivative of the function ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian of a vector-valued function in several variables generalizes the gradient of a scalar-valued function in several variables, which in turn generalizes the derivative of a scalar-valued function of a single variable.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In other words, the Jacobian matrix of a scalar-valued function of several variables is (the transpose of) its gradient and the gradient of a scalar-valued function of a single variable is its derivative.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] At each point where a function is differentiable, its Jacobian matrix can also be thought of as describing the amount of "stretching", "rotating" or "transforming" that the function imposes locally near that point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] For example, if (*x*′, *y*′) = **f**(*x*, *y*) is used to smoothly transform an image, the Jacobian matrix **J****f**(*x*, *y*), describes how the image in the neighborhood of (*x*, *y*) is transformed.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If a function is differentiable at a point, its differential is given in coordinates by the Jacobian matrix.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] However, a function does not need to be differentiable for its Jacobian matrix to be defined, since only its first-order partial derivatives are required to exist.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If **f** is differentiable at a point **p** in **R***n*, then its differential is represented by **J****f**(**p**).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] where *o*(‖**x** − **p**‖) is a quantity that approaches zero much faster than the distance between **x** and **p** does as **x** approaches **p**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In this sense, the Jacobian may be regarded as a kind of "first-order derivative" of a vector-valued function of several variables.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In particular, this means that the gradient of a scalar-valued function of several variables may too be regarded as its "first-order derivative".
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian of the gradient of a scalar function of several variables has a special name: the Hessian matrix, which in a sense is the "second derivative" of the function in question.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If *m* = *n*, then **f** is a function from **R***n* to itself and the Jacobian matrix is a square matrix.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] We can then form its determinant, known as the **Jacobian determinant**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant is sometimes simply referred to as "the Jacobian".
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant at a given point gives important information about the behavior of **f** near that point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] For instance, the continuously differentiable function **f** is invertible near a point **p** ∈ **R***n* if the Jacobian determinant at **p** is non-zero.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Furthermore, if the Jacobian determinant at **p** is positive, then **f** preserves orientation near **p**; if it is negative, **f** reverses orientation.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The absolute value of the Jacobian determinant at **p** gives us the factor by which the function **f** expands or shrinks volumes near **p**; this is why it occurs in the general substitution rule.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant is used when making a change of variables when evaluating a multiple integral of a function over a region within its domain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] To accommodate for the change of coordinates the magnitude of the Jacobian determinant arises as a multiplicative factor within the integral.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] This is because the *n*-dimensional *dV* element is in general a parallelepiped in the new coordinate system, and the *n*-volume of a parallelepiped is the determinant of its edge vectors.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian can also be used to determine the stability of equilibria for systems of differential equations by approximating behavior near an equilibrium point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] According to the inverse function theorem, the matrix inverse of the Jacobian matrix of an invertible function **f** : **R***n* → **R***n* is the Jacobian matrix of the *inverse* function.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If the Jacobian is continuous and nonsingular at the point **p** in **R***n*, then **f** is invertible when restricted to some neighbourhood of **p**.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In other words, if the Jacobian determinant is not zero at a point, then the function is *locally invertible* near this point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The (unproved) Jacobian conjecture is related to global invertibility in the case of a polynomial function, that is a function defined by *n* polynomials in *n* variables.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] It asserts that, if the Jacobian determinant is a non-zero constant (or, equivalently, that it does not have any complex zero), then the function is invertible and its inverse is a polynomial function.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If **f** : **R***n* → **R***m* is a differentiable function, a *critical point* of **f** is a point where the rank of the Jacobian matrix is not maximal.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] This means that the rank at the critical point is lower than the rank at some neighbour point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In other words, let *k* be the maximal dimension of the open balls contained in the image of **f**; then a point is critical if all minors of rank *k* of **f** are zero.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] In the case where *m* = *n* = *k*, a point is critical if the Jacobian determinant is zero.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian determinant is equal to *r*.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Since *dV* = *dx* *dy* *dz* is the volume for a rectangular differential volume element (because the volume of a rectangular prism is the product of its sides), we can interpret *dV* = *ρ*2 sin *φ* *dρ* *dφ* *dθ* as the volume of the spherical differential volume element.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Unlike rectangular differential volume element's volume, this differential volume element's volume is not a constant, and varies with coordinates (*ρ* and *φ*).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] This example shows that the Jacobian matrix need not be a square matrix.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] From this we see that **F** reverses orientation near those points where *x*1 and *x*2 have the same sign; the function is locally invertible everywhere except near points where *x*1 = 0 or *x*2 = 0.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Intuitively, if one starts with a tiny object around the point (1, 2, 3) and apply **F** to that object, one will get a resulting object with approximately 40 × 1 × 2 = 80 times the volume of the original one, with orientation reversed.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Consider a dynamical system of the form ${\dot {\mathbf {x} }}=F(\mathbf {x} )$ , where ${\dot {\mathbf {x} }}$ is the (component-wise) derivative of $\mathbf {x}$ with respect to the evolution parameter t (time), and $F\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is differentiable.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If $F(\mathbf {x} _{0})=0$ , then $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ is a stationary point (also called a steady state).
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] By the Hartman–Grobman theorem, the behavior of the system near a stationary point is related to the eigenvalues of $\mathbf {J} _{F}\left(\mathbf {x} _{0}\right)$ , the Jacobian of F at the stationary point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] Specifically, if the eigenvalues all have real parts that are negative, then the system is stable near the stationary point.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If any eigenvalue has a real part that is positive, then the point is unstable.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] If the largest real part of the eigenvalues is zero, the Jacobian matrix does not allow for an evaluation of the stability.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] A square system of coupled nonlinear equations can be solved iteratively by Newton's method.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] This method uses the Jacobian matrix of the system of equations.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian serves as a linearized design matrix in statistical regression and curve fitting; see non-linear least squares.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/jacobian-matrix-and-determinant] The Jacobian is also used in random matrices, moments, local sensitivity and statistical diagnostics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Robot kinematics studies the relationship between the dimensions and connectivity of kinematic chains and the position, velocity and acceleration of each of the links in the robotic system, in order to plan and control movement and to compute actuator forces and torques.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The relationship between mass and inertia properties, motion, and the associated forces and torques is studied as part of robot dynamics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] A fundamental tool in robot kinematics is the kinematics equations of the kinematic chains that form the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] These non-linear equations are used to map the joint parameters to the configuration of the robot system.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Kinematics equations are also used in biomechanics of the skeleton and computer animation of articulated characters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Forward kinematics uses the kinematic equations of a robot to compute the position of the end effector from specified values for the joint parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The reverse process that computes the joint parameters that achieve a specified position of the end effector is known as inverse kinematics.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The dimensions of the robot and its kinematics equations define the volume of space reachable by the robot, known as its workspace.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] There are two broad classes of robots and associated kinematics equations: serial manipulators and parallel manipulators.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Other types of systems with specialized kinematics equations are air, land, and submersible mobile robots, hyper-redundant, or snake, robots and humanoid robots.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] In forward kinematics (FK), the joint parameters are specified, resulting in values of the end effectors.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] For serial manipulators, the chain configuration is achieved by direct substitution of the joint parameters into the FK equations for the serial chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] For parallel manipulators, substitution of the joint parameters into the kinematics equations requires solution of the a set of polynomial constraints to determine the set of possible end-effector locations.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] In inverse kinematics (IK), the end-effector values are specified and the associated joint angles computed.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] For serial manipulators, this requires solution of a set of polynomials obtained from the kinematics equations and yields multiple configurations for the chain.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The case of a general 6R serial manipulator (a serial chain with six revolute joints) yields 16 different IK solutions, which are solutions of a 16th degree polynomial.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] For parallel manipulators, the specification of the end-effector location simplifies the kinematics equations, which yields formulas for the joint parameters.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The time derivative of the kinematics equations yields the Jacobian of the robot, which relates the joint rates to the linear and angular velocity of the end-effector.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The principle of virtual work shows that the Jacobian also provides a relationship between joint torques and the resultant force and torque applied by the end-effector.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Singular configurations of the robot are identified by studying its Jacobian.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The robot Jacobian results in a set of linear equations that relate the joint rates to the six-vector formed from the angular and linear velocity of the end-effector, known as a twist.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Specifying the joint rates yields the end-effector twist directly.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The **inverse velocity** problem seeks the joint rates that provide a specified end-effector twist.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] This is solved by inverting the Jacobian matrix.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] It can happen that the robot is in a configuration where the Jacobian does not have an inverse.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] These are termed singular configurations of the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The principle of virtual work yields a set of linear equations that relate the resultant force-torque six vector, called a wrench, that acts on the end-effector to the joint torques of the robot.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] If the end-effector wrench is known, then a direct calculation yields the joint torques.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] The **inverse statics** problem seeks the end-effector wrench associated with a given set of joint torques, and requires the inverse of the Jacobian matrix.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] As in the case of inverse velocity analysis, at singular configurations this problem cannot be solved.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] However, near singularities small actuator torques result in a large end-effector wrench.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Thus near singularity configurations robots have large mechanical advantage.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/robot-kinematics] Robot kinematics also deals with motion planning, singularity avoidance, redundancy, collision avoidance, as well as the kinematic synthesis of robots.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] The technique was introduced in 1988 by Nadia Magnenat Thalmann, Richard Laperrière, and Daniel Thalmann.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] This technique is used in virtually all animation systems where simplified user interfaces allow animators to control often complex algorithms and a huge amount of geometry; most notably through inverse kinematics and other "goal-oriented" techniques.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] This technique constructs a series of bones (which need not correspond to any real-world anatomical feature), sometimes also referred to as rigging in the noun sense.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Each bone has a three-dimensional transformation from the default bind pose (which includes its position, scale and orientation), and an optional parent bone.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] The full transform of a child node is the product of its parent transform and its own transform.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] So moving a thigh-bone will move the lower leg too.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] As the character is animated, the bones change their transformation over time, under the influence of some animation controller.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] A rig is generally composed of both forward kinematics and inverse kinematics parts that may interact with each other.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is referring to the forward kinematics part of the rig, where a complete set of bone configurations identifies a unique pose.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Each bone in the skeleton is associated with some portion of the character's visual representation (the mesh) in a process called skinning.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] In the most common case of a polygonal mesh character, the bone is associated with a group of vertices; for example, in a model of a human being, the bone for the thigh would be associated with the vertices making up the polygons in the model's thigh.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Portions of the character's skin can normally be associated with multiple bones, each one having a scaling factor called vertex weights, or blend weights.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] The movement of skin near the joints of two bones, can therefore be influenced by both bones.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] In most state-of-the-art graphical engines, the skinning process is done on the GPU by a shader program.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] For a polygonal mesh, each vertex can have a blend weight for each bone.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] To calculate the final position of the vertex, a transformation matrix is created for each bone which, when applied to the vertex, first puts the vertex in bone space then puts it back into mesh space.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] After applying a matrix to the vertex, it is scaled by its corresponding weight.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] This algorithm is called matrix-palette skinning or linear-blend skinning, because the set of bone transformations (stored as transform matrices) form a palette for the skin vertex to choose from.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is the standard way to animate characters or mechanical objects for a prolonged period of time.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] It is commonly used by video game artists and in the film industry, and can also be applied to mechanical objects and any other objects made up of rigid elements and joints.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Performance capture (or motion capture) can speed up the process of skeletal animation, as well as increasing the level of realism.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Rigs may be driven by ragdoll physics which automatically calculate physics of motion and resistance with skeletal frames.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Virtual anatomy properties such as weight of limbs, muscle reaction, bone strength, and joint constraints may be added for realistic bouncing, buckling, fracture, and tumbling effects.
[src:inverse-kinematics-games/skeletal-animation] Some popular software packages within which rigs may be created include Blender, Autodesk Maya, SideFX Houdini, Autodesk 3ds Max, Maxon Cinema 4D, Unreal Engine, and many others.
